<img src="/c/1802/430396-625x325.jpg?2" alt="#Budget2018: Drought-ravaged provinces could get up to R6bn in relief" width="625" height="325">© Stefano Carnevali – 123RF.comDrought is badly affecting the Western Cape, Eastern Cape, Northern Cape, Free State and parts of KwaZulu-Natal. Gigaba said the national government would commit R6bn to help with drought interventions and infrastructure. He said the government would use the Expanded Public Works Programme to mitigate all serious economic effects of the drought, including the loss of jobs."Government is concerned by the potential job losses in vulnerable farming communities as a result of the drought. We are therefore exploring the option of partially mitigating losses by temporarily increasing intake in the Working for Water programme," he said.<img src="/c/1802/429805-120x120.jpg?2" alt="#SONA2018: Nation called to conserve water amid protracted drought" width="120" height="120">#SONA2018: Nation called to conserve water amid protracted droughtWith a national state of disaster having been declared in three provinces, newly elected President Cyril Ramaphosa has appealed to the nation to continue to intensify efforts to use water wisely...3 days agoThe minister added: "To provide short-term assistance, this budget includes disaster relief grants for provinces and municipalities worth R473m in 2018-19. Other conditional grants can also be reprioritised to respond to disasters if necessary."Source: BDpro